Over the past 10,000 years or so we have been in a relatively warm \'91interglacial\'92 period that was preceded by a \'91glacial\'92 period in which nearly all of Canada and much of Northern Europe were covered by large ice sheets. This oscillating between glacial and interglacial states has been a normal feature of Earth\'92s climate over the past 3-4 million years. These glacial cycles have been driven by cyclical changes in Earth\'92s orbit and tilt that change the distribution of sunlight reaching Earth. If summer sunlight isn\'92t strong enough to melt winter snow in certain places than that snow will stay around and slowly accumulate year after year. If this happens in the Northern Hemisphere, than a glacial climate can occur (the Southern Hemisphere doesn\'92t have enough land in the right places to grow significant ice sheets).  \
\
In the natural course of events, the Earth would return to glacial climate. The glacial/interglacial cycles have taken 100,000 years overall, but the interglacial intervals have usually been short, only about 10,000 years, and this is how long our current interglacial interval has already lasted (Hays, Imbrie, and Shackleton 1976). However a few interglacials have lasted 50,000 years and Earth\'92s orbital features now fairly closely match those longer interglacials. So it is entirely possible that the natural future evolution of Earth\'92s climate would be continued warmth for the next 40,000 years followed by a gradual transition into an ice age. \
\
The effect of the long tail of fossil fuel \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) in the atmosphere (see figure above) will be to make it harder for ice sheets to nucleate and begin to grow in the Northern Hemisphere. The fossil fuel era will likely make Earth skip at least two glacial periods, delaying the next ice age for up to 500,000 years (Archer and Ganapolski 2005). \
